âœ… PostgreSQL â€“ List ALL Indexes in the Database

ðŸ”¹ 1. List all indexes (simple & most-used)

SELECT
    schemaname,
    tablename,
    indexname,
    indexdef
FROM pg_indexes
ORDER BY schemaname, tablename;

âœ” Gives:

Schema name

Table name

Index name

Full index definition (very useful for audits / performance review)



---

ðŸ”¹ 2. List indexes with index type (BTREE, GIN, etc.)

SELECT
    ns.nspname AS schema_name,
    tbl.relname AS table_name,
    idx.relname AS index_name,
    am.amname AS index_type
FROM pg_class idx
JOIN pg_index i ON i.indexrelid = idx.oid
JOIN pg_class tbl ON tbl.oid = i.indrelid
JOIN pg_namespace ns ON ns.oid = tbl.relnamespace
JOIN pg_am am ON idx.relam = am.oid
ORDER BY schema_name, table_name;

âœ” Helpful when checking:

BTREE vs GIN vs GiST

Index strategy issues



---

ðŸ”¹ 3. Indexes for a specific table

SELECT
    indexname,
    indexdef
FROM pg_indexes
WHERE tablename = 'your_table_name';


---

ðŸ”¹ 4. Index size (important for large DBs)

SELECT
    schemaname,
    tablename,
    indexname,
    pg_size_pretty(pg_relation_size(indexname::regclass)) AS index_size
FROM pg_indexes
ORDER BY pg_relation_size(indexname::regclass) DESC;

âœ” Very useful for:

Identifying bloated indexes

Cleanup during migration



---

âœ… MySQL â€“ List Indexes

ðŸ”¹ All indexes in all tables

SELECT
    TABLE_SCHEMA,
    TABLE_NAME,
    INDEX_NAME,
    COLUMN_NAME,
    INDEX_TYPE
FROM information_schema.STATISTICS
ORDER BY TABLE_SCHEMA, TABLE_NAME;


---

âœ… Oracle â€“ List Indexes

SELECT
    OWNER,
    TABLE_NAME,
    INDEX_NAME,
    INDEX_TYPE
FROM ALL_INDEXES
ORDER BY OWNER, TABLE_NAME;


---

âœ… SQL Server â€“ List Indexes

SELECT
    s.name AS schema_name,
    t.name AS table_name,
    i.name AS index_name,
    i.type_desc AS index_type
FROM sys.indexes i
JOIN sys.tables t ON i.object_id = t.object_id
JOIN sys.schemas s ON t.schema_id = s.schema_id
WHERE i.name IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY schema_name, table_name;


